properties.text: Britain's first female Prime Minister walked into number ten amid political upheaval. Serving three terms,the 'Iron Lady' was one of the dominant political figures of 20th century Britain

Growing out of the punk movement of the late 1970s, swearing, sex and scandal ensured the group made the headlines. The lyrics to Sex Pistols' 'God Save the Queen' were deemed so controversial that the BBC refused to play it.

The 1970s marked a difficult decade for Britain, both politically and economically. The country was reduced to a three day working week and suffered a 'Winter of Discontent' with widespread strikes. But power cuts and walk-outs were met with punk and glam rock. While the country struggled economically, social change continued with a 'second wave' of feminism and by the end of the decade, the first female Prime Minister was in Downing Street.

From a galaxy 'far, far away' came Jedis, lightsabers, and 'the force'. The biggest film of the decade, George Lucas' epic space odyssey had a major cultural impact and developed a huge cult-following.
